<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 4:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If264afa16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="Ib978dbb0933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Procedure Before the Panel</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94edf72ae1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:5.</label.designator><headtext>Initiating Panel proceedings—Notice</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>If the Panel initiates transfer, it is required by the statute to give notice of the proposed transfer and of the time and place of hearing. <eos/><bos/>This notice must be given to all parties in all actions in which transfer is contemplated.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If264d6b06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A party may initiate transfer proceedings by filing a motion for transfer with the Panel. <eos/><bos/>The statute requires the moving party to file a copy of the motion in the court in which the moving party&apos;s action is pending.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If264d6b26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] The rules of the Panel additionally require that a copy of the motion for transfer be filed in every other district court in which an action is pending that will be affected by the motion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If26636406b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>If there are defendants who have not been served with process in the action, notice becomes problematical. <eos/><bos/>The Panel has ruled, though, that it can order transfer in that circumstance, although it will look at the litigation more carefully to insure that all facts are known to it and all positions represented.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If26636426b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] The Panel will also grant a hearing to any party who did not receive notice before an action was transferred.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If264afa16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If264d6b06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304913972" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I5436c2506b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407(c)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The statute is reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If264d6b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If264d6b26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304913972" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I54375e906b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407(c)(ii)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The statute is reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If2660f306b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>Detailed information on the Panel&apos;s e-filing system is available in its CM/ECF Users Manual (October 2010), available for review or download at: http://www.jpml.uscourts.gov/Panel_CM_ECF/JPML_CMECF_Attorney_Users_Manual_10-2010.pdf.</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If26636406b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913972" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR6.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I543a1db06b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 6.2(a)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel rules are reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If26636416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If26636426b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The problem of unserved defendants is discussed in greater detail in Chapter 3. See particularly <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:4" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If26636436b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:4</cite.query> n.4 and accompanying quotation and text.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 4:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
